        Level-2 Opponent's Attack: {"claim": "The status quo creates harmful power dynamics and cults of personality.", "argument": ["The status quo creates power dynamics.", "The status quo fosters harmful cults of personality.", "Authors must leverage their names to dismantle these power dynamics."]}
        Level-2 Opponent's Attack: {"claim": "Authors' characteristics and experiences remain embedded in their writing, even under pseudonymity.", "argument": ["Authors' characteristics and experiences remain embedded in their writing.", "The claim that pseudonymity hinders the creation of revolutionary works is wrong."]}
        Level-2 Opponent's Attack: {"claim": "Shared experiences within the text foster connection, regardless of the author\u2019s revealed name.", "argument": ["Shared experiences within the text foster connection.", "Connection is possible regardless of the author's revealed name."]}
        Level-2 Opponent's Attack: {"claim": "The insatiable hunger for fame actively deteriorates good writing.", "argument": ["The insatiable hunger for fame actively deteriorates good writing.", "The opponents failed to address the harms of the status quo."]}
    Level-1 Your Main Claim: {"claim": "Pseudonymity hinders the decolonization of cultural spaces.", "argument": ["Pseudonymity makes it difficult to promote and celebrate marginalized artists.", "Pseudonymity perpetuates existing power imbalances within artistic and academic institutions.", "Understanding the context of historical figures is crucial to critically analyzing their work, and pseudonymity would erase this context."]}
    Level-1 Your Main Claim: {"claim": "Open critique, even if harsh, is crucial for holding individuals accountable and fostering dialogue.", "argument": ["Regressive reactions are preferable to the silencing and erasure caused by forced pseudonymity.", "Open critique is crucial for holding individuals accountable and fostering dialogue.", "Pseudonymity will not prevent censorship and suppression by authoritarian regimes.", "Pseudonymity diminishes the power of dissenting voices."]}
    Level-1 Your Main Claim: {"claim": "Mandated pseudonymity weakens the ability of marginalized voices to challenge oppressive structures and achieve meaningful social change.", "argument": ["Mandated pseudonymity weakens the ability of marginalized voices to challenge oppressive structures.", "Mandated pseudonymity weakens the ability of marginalized voices to achieve meaningful social change."]}
    Level-1 Your Main Claim: {"claim": "Mandatory anonymity removes vital incentives for creating valuable writing and art.", "argument": ["Reputational benefits (fame, validation, career opportunities) incentivize valuable writing and art.", "Mandatory anonymity severs the connection between work and reputation.", "This disincentivizes the creation of valuable writing and art.", "Pseudonyms cannot fully replace the benefits of associating one's name with their work.", "This undermines the marketplace of ideas and diminishes public discourse."]}
    Level-1 Your Main Claim: {"claim": "Mandatory anonymity hinders social progress by obscuring systemic bias and power dynamics.", "argument": ["Credibility cannot be judged solely on writing quality due to systemic bias.", "Anonymity makes it difficult to account for author positionality and biases.", "Anonymity obscures existing power dynamics and makes them harder to challenge.", "The status quo, while imperfect, allows for scrutiny and accountability."]}
    Level-1 Your Main Claim: {"claim": "Authors already strategically choose pseudonyms when necessary, and universal pseudonymity removes that choice and could increase surveillance.", "argument": ["Authors already strategically choose pseudonyms when necessary.", "This motion removes that choice.", "Signaling credibility remains possible even under a pseudonym.", "The government's ability to uncover identities remains unchanged.", "Universal pseudonymity could increase surveillance."]}
    Level-1 Your Main Claim: {"claim": "Mandatory pseudonymity attacks the right to own and benefit from intellectual labor.", "argument": ["The motion attacks the right to own and benefit from intellectual labor.", "It removes crucial incentives for valuable contributions to society.", "It hinders our ability to critically engage with information."]}
